President Donald Trump has announced his intention to nominate two individuals to key positions in his administration. The first nominee is Michael K. Atkinson of Maryland, who is being considered for the position of Inspector General of the Intelligence Community in the Office of the Director of National Intelligence. Atkinson has previously served as an Acting Deputy Assistant Attorney General and Senior Counsel to the Assistant Attorney General of the National Security Division of the Department of Justice. He has also worked as an Assistant United States Attorney in the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of Columbia and as a Trial Attorney in the Fraud Section of the Criminal Division of the Department of Justice. Before entering public service, Atkinson was a partner at Winston and Strawn LLP in Washington D.C.

The second nominee is Linda Capuano of Texas, who is being considered for the position of Administrator of the Energy Information Administration in the Department of Energy. Capuano is currently a Ph.D. fellow at Rice University's Baker Institute for Public Policy's Center for Energy Studies. She has previously held positions at Marathon Oil Corporation, Solectron Flextronics, Advanced Energy Industries, Honeywell, and AlliedSignal Aerospace. Capuano also co-founded and served as chief financial officer of Conductus, a Silicon Valley start-up. She currently serves on the board of Peak Reliability and has served on the Board of the California Independent Systems Operator. Capuano is an associate member of the National Academy of Sciences and holds a Ph.D. and M.S. from Stanford University, an M.S. and B.S. from the University of Colorado at Boulder, and a B.S. from the State University of New York at Stony Brook.